# SI base unit of electric current

For other uses, you might try [Ampere (disambiguation)](/Ampere_(disambiguation)), though I wouldn't recommend it. Some things are best left unambiguous.

ampere
A rather elaborate [ammeter](/Ammeter) demonstration model, designed to illustrate the raw mechanics. As the current threads its way through the coil, the plunger is inexorably drawn further in, and the pointer, with a certain theatrical flourish, swings to the right. A simple illustration of a fundamental principle, for those who need to see the invisible.
General information [Unit system](/System_of_units_of_measurement) [SI](/SI) Unit&#160;of [electric current](/Electric_current) Symbol A Named after [André-Marie Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re)

The [ampere](/Ampere), pronounced either ([/ˈæmpɛər/](/Help:IPA/English)&#32; [ⓘ](/File:LL-Q1860_(eng)-Naomi_Persephone_Amethyst_(NaomiAmethyst)-ampere.wav) AM-pair ) or, if you insist on being American about it, ([US](/American_English): [/ˈæmpɪər/](/Help:IPA/English)&#32; [ⓘ](/File:LL-Q1860_(eng)-Naomi_Persephone_Amethyst_(NaomiAmethyst)-ampere_(alt).wav) AM-peer ), [^1][^2][^3] and often mercifully [shortened](/Clipping_(morphology)) to a mere 'amp' [^4], stands as the foundational unit of [electric current](/Electric_current) within the venerable, and occasionally frustrating, [International System of Units](/International_System_of_Units) (SI). To grasp its essence, simply imagine a single [coulomb](/Coulomb) (C) of electric charge, that rather significant packet of elementary particles, gracefully passing a designated point every single second. [^5][^6][^7] That, my dear, is precisely one ampere. It's a tribute, as most things are, to a human: the [French](/France) polymath [André-Marie Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re) (1775–1836). He, along with his contemporary, the [Danish](/Denmark) physicist [Hans Christian Ørsted](/Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted), is widely, and perhaps justly, credited as a progenitor of the field of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism). They were among the first to truly peel back the layers of this particular cosmic interaction, revealing the intricate dance between electricity and magnetism.

As of the rather significant [2019 revision of the SI](/2019_revision_of_the_SI), the ampere shed its more cumbersome, macroscopic definition for something far more elegant, if a touch more abstract. It is now precisely defined by fixing the numerical value of the [elementary charge](/Elementary_charge) *e* to be an exact 1.602176634×10 −19 &#160;[coulombs](/Coulomb). [^5][^8] What this means, in practical terms, is that an ampere represents an [electric current](/Electric_current) where a colossal 10<sup>19</sup> [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) are flowing past a point every 1.602176634 seconds. Or, if you prefer a slightly more intuitive, albeit still dizzying, figure, it's roughly 6.241509074×10<sup>18</sup> [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) making their exodus in a single second. Prior to this redefinition, the ampere clung to a more tangible, if less precise, concept: it was the constant current that, when maintained in two infinitely long, parallel conductors separated by 1 [metre](/Metre) in a vacuum, would produce a magnetic force of exactly 2×10<sup>−7</sup> [newtons](/Newton_(unit)) per metre of length between them. A rather poetic, if entirely impractical, way to define something so fundamental.

Of course, before the SI decided to bring some semblance of order to the universe, the [CGS system](/Centimetre%E2%80%93gram%E2%80%93second_system_of_units) (Centimetre–Gram–Second system, for those who enjoy historical tangents) offered its own peculiar flavor of units. It provided two distinct units for current. One was structured in a manner vaguely reminiscent of the SI's eventual approach, attempting to quantify the flow. The other, however, took a more fundamental route, defining its unit of charge through [Coulomb's law](/Coulomb%27s_law) – by directly measuring the force exerted between two charged metal plates. Only then, and with a rather circuitous logic, was the CGS unit of current subsequently defined as the passage of one such unit of charge per second. [^9] Because, clearly, simplicity was not a priority.

## History

• Main article: [International System of Electrical and Magnetic Units](/International_System_of_Electrical_and_Magnetic_Units)

The very name 'ampere' is a direct homage to the monumental contributions of the [French](/France) physicist and mathematician, [André-Marie Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re) (1775–1836). This individual, whose intellect seemed to span the cosmos, dedicated significant portions of his life to unraveling the mysteries of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism), ultimately laying down the foundational principles of what we now call [electrodynamics](/Electrodynamics). His work was so profoundly impactful that, in a rare moment of international consensus, an international convention held at the illustrious 1881 [International Exposition of Electricity](/International_Exposition_of_Electricity) formally recognized his genius. It was there, amidst the glittering displays of nascent electrical marvels, that the ampere was officially enshrined as the standard unit for measuring [electric current](/Electric_current). A rather fitting legacy, if you ask me, considering how many people still struggle to grasp what it actually *is*.

Before its modern apotheosis, the ampere began its journey as a mere fraction – specifically, one tenth – of the unit of [electric current](/Electric_current) within the rather convoluted [centimetre–gram–second system of units](/Centimetre%E2%80%93gram%E2%80%93second_system_of_units). This earlier unit, which now carries the rather archaic designation of the [abampere](/Abampere), was itself defined by a force-based criterion. It represented the precise amount of current that, flowing through two parallel wires separated by a single centimetre, would generate a repulsive or attractive force of two [dynes](/Dyne) per centimetre of their length. [^10] The specific magnitude of this unit wasn't chosen arbitrarily; it was meticulously selected to ensure that the units subsequently derived from it within the [MKSA](/MKS_system_of_units) (Metre-Kilogram-Second-Ampere) system would possess conveniently manageable sizes for practical applications. A rare instance of foresight, perhaps.

For a time, there existed an "international ampere," an early, somewhat less precise, physical realization of the unit. This definition was rooted in electrochemistry, stipulating that one international ampere was the current required to deposit precisely 0.001118&#160;grams of silver per second from a [silver nitrate](/Silver_nitrate) solution. It was a tangible, if chemically messy, way to define an electrical quantity. However, as the instruments of measurement grew more sophisticated and human precision improved, subsequent, more accurate measurements revealed a slight discrepancy: this "international ampere" was actually equivalent to approximately 0.99985&#160;A of the later, more rigorously defined standard. [^11] A testament to the ever-present gap between theoretical ideals and messy reality.

Given that [power](/Power_(physics)) (P) is fundamentally defined as the product of current (I) and voltage (V), the ampere can also be elegantly expressed in terms of these other units through the simple relationship *I* = *P* / *V*. Consequently, 1&#160;A is equivalent to 1&#160;[watt](/Watt) per [volt](/Volt) (1&#160;W/V). For those who prefer a more hands-on approach, current is typically measured using a [multimeter](/Multimeter), that ubiquitous device found in every engineer's toolkit, capable of simultaneously quantifying electrical voltage, current, and resistance. It's almost as if they designed it to make your life easier.

## Former definition in the SI

Until the aforementioned, and frankly overdue, 2019 revision, the SI clung to a definition of the ampere that, while conceptually grand, was a nightmare to actually implement. It stated:

> The ampere is that constant current which, if maintained in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, of negligible circular cross-section, and placed one [metre](/Metre) apart in vacuum, would produce between these conductors a force equal to 2×10<sup>−7</sup> [newtons](/Newton_(unit)) per metre of length. [^12]:&#8202;113&#8202; [^13]

Just try to visualize that. Infinite length, negligible cross-section, perfect vacuum. It sounds less like a scientific definition and more like a philosophical thought experiment. This definition, derived directly from [Ampère's force law](/Amp%C3%A8re%27s_force_law) [^14][^15], which describes the attractive or repulsive force between two parallel wires carrying an [electric current](/Electric_current), had a rather significant implication. It effectively fixed the value of the [vacuum magnetic permeability](/Vacuum_permeability) (often referred to as the magnetic constant, μ<sub>0</sub>) to be precisely 4π&#160;×&#160;10<sup>−7</sup> [henries](/Henry_(unit)) per metre (H/m), which is dimensionally equivalent to [newtons](/Newton_(unit)) per square ampere (N/A<sup>2</sup>). Following from this, the SI unit of charge, the [coulomb](/Coulomb), was then defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere." [^12]:&#8202;144&#8202; This established a direct, if somewhat circular, relationship where charge *Q* was determined by a steady current *I* flowing for a time *t* as *Q* = *It*.

The most accurate practical realization of this definition of the ampere was typically achieved using a [Kibble balance](/Kibble_balance) (formerly known as a watt balance), a marvel of metrology that relates electrical power to mechanical power. However, in routine laboratory practice, the unit was more commonly maintained indirectly, through [Ohm's law](/Ohm%27s_law), leveraging the units of [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) (voltage) and [resistance](/Electrical_resistance_and_conductance): the [volt](/Volt) and the [ohm](/Ohm), respectively. This was a pragmatic choice, as the latter two units could be tied to remarkably stable and reproducible quantum phenomena – specifically, the [Josephson effect](/Josephson_effect) for voltage and the [quantum Hall effect](/Quantum_Hall_effect) for resistance. [^16] These quantum effects offer an intrinsic, universal standard, a rare anchor in the shifting sands of physical measurement.

Despite the theoretical elegance, the techniques employed to establish a practical realization of an ampere under this former definition still carried a [relative uncertainty](/Approximation_error) of approximately a few parts in 10<sup>7</sup>. These methods were complex, often involving intricate realizations of the [watt](/Watt), the [ohm](/Ohm), and the [volt](/Volt) to indirectly arrive at the ampere. [^16] It was a bit like trying to measure the exact height of a mountain by observing its shadow, the moon's phase, and the precise angle of a particularly uncooperative cloud. Possible, but unnecessarily complex.

## Present definition

The [2019 revision of the SI](/2019_revision_of_the_SI) finally brought the ampere into the modern age, grounding it in a fundamental constant of nature rather than an idealized, unachievable experiment. The ampere is now defined by taking the fixed numerical value of the [elementary charge](/Elementary_charge) *e* to be exactly 1.602176634×10<sup>−19</sup> when expressed in the unit [coulomb](/Coulomb) (C). The [coulomb](/Coulomb) itself is, of course, equal to A⋅s (ampere-second), and the [second](/Second) is rigorously defined in terms of ∆*ν*<sub>Cs</sub>, the unperturbed ground state hyperfine transition frequency of the [caesium](/Caesium)-133 atom. [^17] This means we've essentially anchored the flow of charge to the immutable properties of the universe, rather than to hypothetical wires in a vacuum. A definite improvement, even if it does sound like something only a quantum physicist could love.

The SI unit of charge, the [coulomb](/Coulomb), remains defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere." [^18] Conversely, and perhaps more usefully, a current of one ampere is now understood as one [coulomb](/Coulomb) of charge – approximately 6.241509×10<sup>18</sup> [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) – passing a given point every single second. Or, to put it even more precisely, it's 10<sup>19</sup> [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) flowing every 1.602176634 seconds. The mathematical expression of this fundamental relationship is rather straightforward, for those who appreciate such things:

$$
1{\text{ A}}=1{\text{ C/s}}={\frac {1}{1.602\,176\,634\times 10^{-19}}}\,e{\text{/s}}={\frac {10^{19}\,e}{1.602\,176\,634{\text{ s}}}}
$$

And, leveraging the definition of the [second](/Second) in terms of ∆*ν*<sub>Cs</sub>, the caesium-133 hyperfine transition frequency, the ampere can also be expressed directly in terms of *e* and ∆*ν*<sub>Cs</sub>: [^19]

$$
1{\text{ A}}=1{\text{ C/s}}={\Big (}{\frac {10^{19}\,e}{1.602\,176\,634}}{\Big )}{\Big (}{\frac {\Delta \nu _{\text{Cs}}}{9\,192\,631\,770}}{\Big )}\approx 6.789\,6868\times 10^{8}\,e\,\Delta \nu _{\text{Cs}}
$$

It's a beautiful, if somewhat dizzying, cascade of fundamental constants. Both constant and instantaneous currents are, naturally, expressed in [amperes](/Ampere) (as in, "the charging current is 1.2&#160;A"), while the total charge that accumulates or passes through a circuit over a specific period is expressed in [coulombs](/Coulomb) (for instance, "the [battery](/Battery_(electricity)) charge is 30000&#160;C"). The relationship between the ampere (A&#160;=&#160;C/s) and the [coulomb](/Coulomb) (C) mirrors the relationship between the [watt](/Watt) (W&#160;=&#160;J/s) and the [joule](/Joule) (J). A simple, elegant symmetry that even *I* can appreciate.

## Units derived from the ampere

The [international system of units](/International_system_of_units) (SI), in its endless quest for comprehensive classification, is built upon a foundation of seven distinct [SI base units](/SI_base_units). These are the [second](/Second), [metre](/Metre), [kilogram](/Kilogram), [kelvin](/Kelvin), [ampere](/Ampere), [mole](/Mole_(unit)), and [candela](/Candela). Each represents a fundamental type of physical quantity, or "dimension" – [time](/Time), [length](/Length), [mass](/Mass), [temperature](/Temperature), [electric current](/Electric_current), [amount of substance](/Amount_of_substance), and [luminous intensity](/Luminous_intensity), respectively. Every other unit in the SI, known as [SI derived units](/SI_derived_units), is meticulously defined using combinations of these base units. These derived units can either be bestowed with their own special names, such as the [watt](/Watt), [volt](/Volt), or [lux](/Lux), or they can be explicitly defined in terms of their constituent base units, like the straightforward [metre per second](/Metre_per_second).

Here are some of the more prominent units that owe their existence, directly or indirectly, to the ampere:

