The [ampere](/Ampere) (pronounced, if you must, as [/ˈæmpɛər/](/Help:IPA/English)&#32; [ⓘ](/File:LL-Q1860_(eng)-Naomi_Persephone_Amethyst_(NaomiAmethyst)-ampere.wav) AM-pair , or with a slightly more nasal, [US](/American_English) inflection: [/ˈæmpɪər/](/Help:IPA/English)&#32; [ⓘ](/File:LL-Q1860_(eng)-Naomi_Persephone_Amethyst_(NaomiAmethyst)-ampere_(alt).wav) AM-peer [^1][^2][^3]), its symbol a rather assertive 'A' [^4], and frequently, lazily, [shortened](/Clipping_(morphology)) to a mere "amp" [^5], is the definitive unit of [electric current](/Electric_current) within the meticulously structured, if occasionally overbearing, [International System of Units](/International_System_of_Units) (SI). At its core, one ampere quantifies the passage of precisely 1 [coulomb](/Coulomb) (C) of electric charge moving past a given point in a circuit every single second. [^6][^7][^8] It's a fundamental rate, a measure of how much electrical 'stuff' is flowing. This pivotal unit bears the name of the extraordinary [French](/France) mathematician and physicist [André-Marie Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re) (1775–1836). Ampère, a figure of profound intellectual depth, is, alongside the equally brilliant [Danish](/Denmark) physicist [Hans Christian Ørsted](/Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted), rightly revered as one of the founding fathers of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism). Their pioneering work transformed humanity's understanding of how these two seemingly disparate forces were inextricably linked, paving the way for virtually all modern electrical technology.

The landscape of fundamental constants shifted significantly with the [2019 revision of the SI](/2019_revision_of_the_SI). Under this updated framework, the ampere is no longer tied to an abstract, idealized experiment involving infinite wires. Instead, it is now precisely defined by fixing the numerical value of the [elementary charge](/Elementary_charge) *e* to be an exact and immutable 1.602176634×10<sup>−19</sup> [coulombs](/Coulomb) (C). [^6][^9] This redefinition means that an ampere can be conceptualized as an [electric current](/Electric_current) where a staggering 10<sup>19</sup> [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) traverse a point every 1.602176634 seconds. For those who prefer their numbers slightly more digestible, this translates to approximately 6.241509074×10<sup>18</sup> [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) moving past a specified point within a mere second. This is a profound shift from the previous definition, which, prior to 2019, stipulated the ampere as the constant current that, when maintained in two infinitely long, perfectly parallel conductors, separated by 1 [metre](/Metre) in the vacuum of space, would generate a magnetic force of precisely 2×10<sup>−7</sup> [newtons](/Newton_(unit)) per metre of their length. A definition that, while elegant in its theoretical purity, was utterly impractical to realize in any meaningful sense.

Before the SI consolidated and standardized the units of measurement, there existed a certain chaotic charm, particularly in the [Centimetre–gram–second system of units](/Centimetre%E2%80%93gram%E2%80%93second_system_of_units) (CGS). This system, in its unique wisdom, offered not one, but two distinct units for [electric current](/Electric_current). One of these was formulated in a manner somewhat analogous to the modern SI approach, focusing on the flow rate of charge. The other, however, took a more circuitous route, directly defining its fundamental unit of charge using [Coulomb's law](/Coulomb%27s_law). This involved measuring the precise force exerted between two charged metal plates, establishing the CGS unit of charge. Only then, once the charge was defined, was the CGS unit of current subsequently derived as the passage of one unit of this charge per second. [^10] It was a system that certainly had its quirks, a testament to the diverse paths early scientists took in grappling with these unseen forces.

## History

• Main article: [International System of Electrical and Magnetic Units](/International_System_of_Electrical_and_Magnetic_Units)

The very name of the [ampere](/Ampere) serves as an enduring tribute to the profound and lasting legacy of the [French](/France) physicist and mathematician, [André-Marie Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re) (1775–1836). This remarkable individual dedicated his considerable intellect to the rigorous study of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism), meticulously observing and quantifying the interactions between electric currents and magnetic fields. His groundbreaking theoretical work effectively laid the indispensable foundations of [electrodynamics](/Electrodynamics), providing the mathematical framework necessary to understand and predict these complex phenomena. In recognition of Ampère's truly seminal contributions to the nascent field of modern electrical science, an international convention was convened. This significant gathering, held during the illustrious 1881 [International Exposition of Electricity](/International_Exposition_of_Electricity) in Paris, formally established the ampere as the universally recognized standard unit of electrical measurement for [electric current](/Electric_current). It was a moment where scientific consensus solidified, giving a name and a quantifiable measure to one of nature's most powerful forces.

Prior to its elevation to a base SI unit, the ampere had a more modest origin. It was initially conceived as precisely one tenth of the unit of [electric current](/Electric_current) within the rather intricate and now largely superseded [centimetre–gram–second system of units](/Centimetre%E2%80%93gram%E2%80%93second_system_of_units). That particular CGS unit, which is now known by the somewhat antiquated moniker of the [abampere](/Abampere), was itself defined by a direct force measurement. It represented the specific amount of current that, when flowing through two infinitely long, perfectly parallel wires separated by one centimetre, would generate a mutual force of two [dynes](/Dyne) per centimetre of their common length. [^11] The precise magnitude of this unit was not arbitrary; it was carefully chosen to ensure that the units subsequently derived from it within the [MKSA](/MKS_system_of_units) (Metre-Kilogram-Second-Ampere) system would be of conveniently practical sizes for engineering and scientific applications, avoiding unwieldy large or small numerical values.

For a period, an "international ampere" served as an early, albeit imperfect, practical realization of the unit. This definition was anchored in a specific electrochemical process: it was defined as the constant current that would precisely deposit 0.001118&#160;grams of pure silver per second from an electrolytic solution of [silver nitrate](/Silver_nitrate). This method offered a reproducible, if slightly cumbersome, way to physically manifest the unit. However, as metrological science advanced and measurement techniques became increasingly refined, more accurate measurements eventually revealed a subtle but significant discrepancy. It was found that this "international ampere" was, in fact, slightly larger than the theoretically precise ampere, equating to approximately 0.99985&#160;A of the later, more rigorously defined standard. [^12] A stark reminder that even the most careful experimental definitions are subject to the relentless march of scientific precision.

Considering that [power](/Power_(physics)) (*P*) is fundamentally defined as the product of [electric current](/Electric_current) (*I*) and [electric potential difference](/Electric_potential_difference) (*V*), expressed as *P* = *IV*, the ampere can be alternatively, and quite elegantly, expressed in terms of these other units. Rearranging this relationship yields *I* = *P* / *V*, which means that 1&#160;A is dimensionally equivalent to 1&#160;[watt](/Watt) per [volt](/Volt) (1&#160;W/V). This interrelationship highlights the cohesive nature of the SI. In practical applications, the measurement of current is typically performed using an [ammeter](/Ammeter), a specialized instrument. Modern devices, often known as [multimeters](/Multimeter), are far more versatile, capable of simultaneously measuring not only electrical current but also voltage and resistance, providing a comprehensive diagnostic tool for electrical circuits.

## Former definition in the SI

Until the pivotal [2019 revision of the SI](/2019_revision_of_the_SI), the ampere was defined in a manner that, while conceptually grand, bordered on the physically unattainable. The official SI definition stated:

> The ampere is that constant current which, if maintained in two straight parallel conductors of infinite length, of negligible circular cross-section, and placed one [metre](/Metre) apart in vacuum, would produce between these conductors a force equal to 2×10<sup>−7</sup> [newtons](/Newton_(unit)) per metre of length. [^13]:&#8202;113&#8202; [^14]

One can almost hear the collective sigh of physicists tasked with actually *realizing* this. The explicit inclusion of "infinite length," "negligible circular cross-section," and "in vacuum" made this definition a theoretical ideal rather than a practical benchmark. This definition was a direct consequence of [Ampère's force law](/Amp%C3%A8re%27s_force_law) [^15][^16], a fundamental principle describing the attractive or repulsive force that manifests between two parallel conductors when they carry an [electric current](/Electric_current). A crucial implication of this definition was that it precisely fixed the value of the [vacuum magnetic permeability](/Vacuum_permeability) (μ<sub>0</sub>), often referred to as the magnetic constant, to be exactly 4π&#160;×&#160;10<sup>−7</sup> [henries](/Henry_(unit)) per metre (H/m). This unit is dimensionally equivalent to [newtons](/Newton_(unit)) per square ampere (N/A<sup>2</sup>). Building upon this, the SI unit of charge, the [coulomb](/Coulomb), was then subsequently defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere." [^13]:&#8202;144&#8202; Thus, in this framework, the total charge *Q* that flowed was determined by a steady current *I* maintained over a time *t*, expressed simply as *Q* = *It*.

The most accurate and sophisticated method for physically realizing this ampere definition involved the use of a [Kibble balance](/Kibble_balance) (historically known as a watt balance). This ingenious device directly links electrical power to mechanical power, allowing for extremely precise measurements. However, in day-to-day metrology and practical applications, the unit was more commonly maintained indirectly, relying on [Ohm's law](/Ohm%27s_law) and the highly stable quantum phenomena associated with the units of [electromotive force](/Electromotive_force) (voltage) and [electrical resistance](/Electrical_resistance_and_conductance): namely, the [volt](/Volt) and the [ohm](/Ohm). These two units could be tied with exquisite precision to the [Josephson effect](/Josephson_effect) (for voltage) and the [quantum Hall effect](/Quantum_Hall_effect) (for resistance), respectively. [^17] These quantum effects provided a fundamental and universal basis for electrical standards, offering a stability that the macroscopic force definition of the ampere simply couldn't match.

Even with these advanced techniques, the practical realization of an ampere under the former definition still carried a [relative uncertainty](/Approximation_error) of approximately a few parts in 10<sup>7</sup>. The processes involved were intricate and demanding, often requiring the precise realization of the [watt](/Watt), the [ohm](/Ohm), and the [volt](/Volt) to then indirectly derive the ampere. [^17] It was a complex, multi-step dance of fundamental units, a testament to the lengths scientists would go to anchor their measurements, even when the primary definition was somewhat ethereal.

## Present definition

The [2019 revision of the SI](/2019_revision_of_the_SI) ushered in a new era for the definition of the ampere, moving away from macroscopic force interactions to a more fundamental constant of nature. Under this contemporary framework, the ampere is now precisely defined by fixing the numerical value of the [elementary charge](/Elementary_charge) *e* to be exactly 1.602176634×10<sup>−19</sup> when expressed in the unit [coulomb](/Coulomb) (C). It's a clean break from the past, tying the ampere directly to the quantum world. The [coulomb](/Coulomb) itself is, of course, dimensionally equivalent to A⋅s (ampere-second), and the [second](/Second) is rigorously defined in terms of ∆*ν*<sub>Cs</sub>, which is the unperturbed ground state hyperfine transition frequency of the [caesium](/Caesium)-133 atom. [^18] This creates an interconnected web of fundamental definitions, all rooted in unchanging physical constants.

The SI unit of charge, the [coulomb](/Coulomb), remains steadfastly defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere." [^19] Conversely, and perhaps more intuitively, a current of one ampere is now understood as the flow of one [coulomb](/Coulomb) of charge – which equates to approximately 6.241509×10<sup>18</sup> individual [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) – passing a given point in a circuit every single second. Alternatively, and with even greater precision, it can be stated as 10<sup>19</sup> [elementary charges](/Elementary_charge) moving past a point every 1.602176634 seconds. The mathematical representation of this definition, for those who appreciate the stark clarity of equations, is as follows:

$$
1{\text{ A}}=1{\text{ C/s}}={\frac {1}{1.602\,176\,634\times 10^{-19}}}\,e{\text{/s}}={\frac {10^{19}\,e}{1.602\,176\,634{\text{ s}}}}
$$

Furthermore, by incorporating the definition of the [second](/Second) in terms of ∆*ν*<sub>Cs</sub>, the caesium-133 hyperfine transition frequency, the ampere can be elegantly expressed directly in terms of both the [elementary charge](/Elementary_charge) *e* and ∆*ν*<sub>Cs</sub>: [^20]

$$
1{\text{ A}}=1{\text{ C/s}}={\Big (}{\frac {10^{19}\,e}{1.602\,176\,634}}{\Big )}{\Big (}{\frac {\Delta \nu _{\text{Cs}}}{9\,192\,631\,770}}{\Big )}\approx 6.789\,6868\times 10^{8}\,e\,\Delta \nu _{\text{Cs}}
$$

This series of relationships underscores the deep interconnections within the SI, where fundamental constants serve as the bedrock for all measurements. Both constant and instantaneous currents are, naturally, expressed in [amperes](/Ampere) (e.g., "the charging current is 1.2&#160;A"), while the total quantity of charge accumulated or passed through a circuit over a specific duration is quantified in [coulombs](/Coulomb) (e.g., "the [battery](/Battery_(electricity)) charge is 30000&#160;C"). The fundamental relationship of the ampere (A&#160;=&#160;C/s) to the [coulomb](/Coulomb) (C) is perfectly analogous to that of the [watt](/Watt) (W&#160;=&#160;J/s) to the [joule](/Joule) (J), illustrating a consistent pattern throughout the system of units. It's almost elegant, in a cold, hard, scientific way.

## Units derived from the ampere

The [international system of units](/International_system_of_units) (SI) is a meticulously constructed framework, built upon seven foundational [SI base units](/SI_base_units). These indispensable pillars are the [second](/Second), [metre](/Metre), [kilogram](/Kilogram), [kelvin](/Kelvin), [ampere](/Ampere), [mole](/Mole_(unit)), and [candela](/Candela). Each of these base units represents a unique fundamental type of physical quantity, or "dimension," encompassing [time](/Time), [length](/Length), [mass](/Mass), [temperature](/Temperature), [electric current](/Electric_current), [amount of substance](/Amount_of_substance), and [luminous intensity](/Luminous_intensity), respectively. From this compact set of seven, all other SI units, known as [SI derived units](/SI_derived_units), are meticulously defined. These derived units can either be granted their own distinctive special names, such as the [watt](/Watt) (for power), the [volt](/Volt) (for potential difference), or the [lux](/Lux) (for illuminance), or they can be expressed directly in terms of their constituent base units, as exemplified by the [metre per second](/Metre_per_second) (for velocity). The ampere, as a base unit, forms the indispensable foundation for a multitude of these derived electrical quantities.

Here is a selection of SI derived units that are fundamentally linked to, or directly incorporate, the ampere in their definition:

| Quantity                      | Unit                                | Symbol | Meaning           | In SI base units           |
| :---------------------------- | :---------------------------------- | :----- | :---------------- | :------------------------- |
| [Electric charge](/Electric_charge)             | [coulomb](/Coulomb)                 | C      | ampere second      | A⋅s                        |
| [Electric potential difference](/Electric_potential_difference) | [volt](/Volt)                       | V      | [joule](/Joule) per coulomb | kg⋅m<sup>2</sup>⋅s<sup>−3</sup>⋅A<sup>−1</sup> |
| [Electrical resistance](/Electrical_resistance)     | [ohm](/Ohm)                         | Ω      | volt per ampere   | kg⋅m<sup>2</sup>⋅s<sup>−3</sup>⋅A<sup>−2</sup> |
| [Electrical conductance](/Electrical_conductance)   | [siemens](/Siemens_(unit))          | S      | ampere per volt or inverse ohm | s<sup>3</sup>⋅A<sup>2</sup>⋅kg<sup>−1</sup>⋅m<sup>−2</sup> |
| [Electrical inductance](/Electrical_inductance)     | [henry](/Henry_(unit))              | H      | ohm second        | kg⋅m<sup>2</sup>⋅s<sup>−2</sup>⋅A<sup>−2</sup> |
| [Electrical capacitance](/Electrical_capacitance)   | [farad](/Farad)                     | F      | coulomb per volt  | s<sup>4</sup>⋅A<sup>2</sup>⋅kg<sup>−1</sup>⋅m<sup>−2</sup> |
| [Magnetic flux](/Magnetic_flux)             | [weber](/Weber_(unit))              | Wb     | volt second       | kg⋅m<sup>2</sup>⋅s<sup>−2</sup>⋅A<sup>−1</sup> |
| [Magnetic flux density](/Magnetic_flux_density)   | [tesla](/Tesla_(unit))              | T      | weber per [square metre](/Square_metre) | kg⋅s<sup>−2</sup>⋅A<sup>−1</sup> |

It's a rather extensive family, wouldn't you agree? Beyond these direct derivations, there are also several other SI units that are frequently encountered in the domains of [electrical engineering](/Electrical_engineering) and when discussing electrical appliances. However, these units are defined independently of the ampere, though they often interact with it in practical contexts. Notable examples include the [hertz](/Hertz) (for frequency), the [joule](/Joule) (for energy), the [watt](/Watt) (for power), the [candela](/Candela) (for luminous intensity, a base unit itself), the [lumen](/Lumen_(unit)) (for luminous flux), and the [lux](/Lux) (for illuminance). Their independence doesn't make them any less relevant, merely less directly descended from the ampere's lineage.

## SI prefixes

• Main article: [Orders of magnitude (current)](/Orders_of_magnitude_(current))

